00:02:24.150 --> 00:02:27.470
My youngest brother-- we're
all very different, competing.

00:02:27.470 --> 00:02:29.380
We're four boys,
very competitive.

00:02:29.380 --> 00:02:31.463
But my youngest brother
is mentally and physically

00:02:31.463 --> 00:02:33.700
handicapped.

00:02:33.700 --> 00:02:38.870
When he was five years old,
he had a fever in Africa

00:02:38.870 --> 00:02:43.060
and it was incredibly
difficult to deal with it.

00:02:43.060 --> 00:02:46.360
The temperature sort of
flipped into sort of a really

00:02:46.360 --> 00:02:50.570
unsustainable level and he
came out two weeks later

00:02:50.570 --> 00:02:51.696
with brain damage.

00:02:51.696 --> 00:02:54.070
So it happened when he was
five and it was very traumatic

00:02:54.070 --> 00:02:55.330
for my family.

00:02:55.330 --> 00:02:57.040
And a way, it was
the time that sort of

00:02:57.040 --> 00:03:00.035
shifted the dynamic of traveling
in my family and my father.

00:03:00.035 --> 00:03:01.160
My father's career changed.

00:03:01.160 --> 00:03:03.820
He became local staff,
rather than carrying on

00:03:03.820 --> 00:03:05.710
as a kind of career diplomat.

00:03:05.710 --> 00:03:08.710
And he chose London
because predominately, we

00:03:08.710 --> 00:03:12.010
had gone to Anglophone
schools, so English schools.

00:03:12.010 --> 00:03:15.400
So he decided that London
was the right place for us

00:03:15.400 --> 00:03:18.940
to stay and to get the care
that he needed for my youngest

00:03:18.940 --> 00:03:21.439
brother, the sort of best
medical care that he could.

00:03:21.439 --> 00:03:23.230
SHIH HUA LIONG: And I
feel like that really

00:03:23.230 --> 00:03:26.470
speaks to the core of who
you are as an architect,

00:03:26.470 --> 00:03:30.040
right, in terms of the social
responsibility of architecture

00:03:30.040 --> 00:03:34.180
and how it can transform
our societies So talk

00:03:34.180 --> 00:03:35.520
to us a little bit about that.

00:03:35.520 --> 00:03:36.228
DAVID ADJAYE: No.

00:03:36.228 --> 00:03:38.650
I mean, in a way, that's
the grounding which

00:03:38.650 --> 00:03:42.580
started my interest in the
nature of space and space

00:03:42.580 --> 00:03:48.400
and society, space and citizens,
space and freedom, space

00:03:48.400 --> 00:03:50.240
and accessibility.

00:03:50.240 --> 00:03:53.500
And it just came
from a young child

00:03:53.500 --> 00:03:57.010
pushing a disabled
brother around everywhere.

00:03:57.010 --> 00:04:02.800
And in the late '80, early '90s,
disability were not around.

00:04:02.800 --> 00:04:05.230
So we would always
be the family that

00:04:05.230 --> 00:04:08.860
were kind of pushing our brother
to the back of a building

00:04:08.860 --> 00:04:11.610
and sort of yanking him up and
getting people to sort of hold

00:04:11.610 --> 00:04:14.929
him to get him up into buildings
because ramps weren't around.

00:04:14.929 --> 00:04:16.720
Very simple things like
ramps and elevators

00:04:16.720 --> 00:04:18.945
that make level access for
people, all these things

00:04:18.945 --> 00:04:19.570
weren't around.

00:04:19.570 --> 00:04:21.790
And it really got me incensed.

00:04:21.790 --> 00:04:24.850
And things like come respite
centers for disabled people,

00:04:24.850 --> 00:04:28.030
places to have good
care would be given,

00:04:28.030 --> 00:04:30.220
those are very ad hoc
and horrible places

00:04:30.220 --> 00:04:33.280
with just sort of infrastructure
that really slightly

00:04:33.280 --> 00:04:35.560
de-humanized the
experience that was already

00:04:35.560 --> 00:04:38.800
a kind of traumatic experience
for people without ability.

00:04:38.800 --> 00:04:41.020
And for some strange
reason, architecture,

00:04:41.020 --> 00:04:44.140
I became very sensitized to it.

00:04:44.140 --> 00:04:49.240
And I decided that it wasn't
just for me about aesthetics

00:04:49.240 --> 00:04:50.870
or monuments or
anything like that,

00:04:50.870 --> 00:04:53.620
but it was also principally
an approach problem-solving,

00:04:53.620 --> 00:04:56.440
but it's also about a kind of
democratizing this knowledge

00:04:56.440 --> 00:04:59.920
to create the greatest
opportunity for everyone

00:04:59.920 --> 00:05:03.730
so that architectural design
is not just for an elite

00:05:03.730 --> 00:05:07.610
or for people who
can afford things.

00:05:07.610 --> 00:05:11.240
It's not about the value of
it, it's about the intellect.

00:05:11.240 --> 00:05:14.070
And if the intellect
is what's being sold,

00:05:14.070 --> 00:05:17.540
then that should be able
kind of be for everyone.

00:05:17.540 --> 00:05:19.820
We like to say in
our office, we really

00:05:19.820 --> 00:05:21.930
believe that luxury
should be for everyone.

00:05:21.930 --> 00:05:23.900
And we don't mean luxury
as in gold, but luxury

00:05:23.900 --> 00:05:27.260
as the capacity to think should
be for a project which is maybe

00:05:27.260 --> 00:05:31.850
making a cafe for a truck
stop in the middle of nowhere

00:05:31.850 --> 00:05:34.850
as much as maybe
working for you guys.

00:05:34.850 --> 00:05:35.830
It's the same.

00:05:35.830 --> 00:05:37.490
SHIH HUA LIONG: Absolutely.

00:05:37.490 --> 00:05:39.800
I think that's a really good
segue to some of the work

00:05:39.800 --> 00:05:42.490
that you're doing here in
New York with the Sugar Hill

00:05:42.490 --> 00:05:44.600
Housing Program in
Harlem, which I'm

00:05:44.600 --> 00:05:47.660
quite familiar with because
it's right down the road for me.

00:05:47.660 --> 00:05:50.439
So 125 units of
affordable housing.

00:05:50.439 --> 00:05:51.230
DAVID ADJAYE: Yeah.

00:05:51.230 --> 00:05:52.040
SHIH HUA LIONG:
Tell us a little bit

00:05:52.040 --> 00:05:54.140
about how you got
that project and what

00:05:54.140 --> 00:05:56.480
it meant to you and
you and even the motifs

00:05:56.480 --> 00:05:58.470
that you see at the
front of the building.

00:05:58.470 --> 00:05:59.261
DAVID ADJAYE: Yeah.

00:05:59.261 --> 00:06:01.970
That was my first big
competition in the city.

00:06:01.970 --> 00:06:04.790
And I really was
very excited about it

00:06:04.790 --> 00:06:07.100
because essentially, the
principal tenant of it

00:06:07.100 --> 00:06:10.550
was to deal with homeless
housing in New York

00:06:10.550 --> 00:06:15.761
and to use design to really talk
about how do you integrate--

00:06:15.761 --> 00:06:18.260
homeless housing usually is
seen as a blight on communities,

00:06:18.260 --> 00:06:20.134
people don't want to
have it near their homes

00:06:20.134 --> 00:06:22.184
because they think it
devalues their property,

00:06:22.184 --> 00:06:24.350
there's all this kind of
stigma with the communities

00:06:24.350 --> 00:06:25.620
that are around it.

00:06:25.620 --> 00:06:28.430
And we said this was a
very important project

00:06:28.430 --> 00:06:31.610
because it deals with a
key and clear social issue

00:06:31.610 --> 00:06:34.730
and that actually, design can
be used to coordinate, solve

00:06:34.730 --> 00:06:37.892
the problem of the sort
of flow and movement

00:06:37.892 --> 00:06:39.850
that happens around these
institutions in terms

00:06:39.850 --> 00:06:42.350
of different types
of people, but also

00:06:42.350 --> 00:06:44.870
that we can also make an
architecture that gives dignity

00:06:44.870 --> 00:06:47.760
to this community
but is not expensive.

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:50.650
It's also in that sort
of low cost budget.

00:06:50.650 --> 00:06:54.110
And it was a big signature
project for DeBlasio.

00:06:54.110 --> 00:06:57.347
It started at the end
of Bloomberg's sort

00:06:57.347 --> 00:06:59.180
of administration and
became DeBlasio's kind

00:06:59.180 --> 00:07:02.420
of signature project to talk
about the importance of housing

00:07:02.420 --> 00:07:03.870
for all.

00:07:03.870 --> 00:07:06.080
So in a way, the architectural
discussion at the time

00:07:06.080 --> 00:07:09.842
was about luxury buildings and
ever more fantastical shapes,

00:07:09.842 --> 00:07:12.050
but actually the kind of
more meaningful conversation

00:07:12.050 --> 00:07:14.660
was happening about,
well, how do we

00:07:14.660 --> 00:07:18.480
get good design right to the
people that need it most?

00:07:18.480 --> 00:07:20.870
Of the building really
speaks to the history

00:07:20.870 --> 00:07:22.850
of its place in
the sense that it

00:07:22.850 --> 00:07:24.740
talks about the
fact that actually,

00:07:24.740 --> 00:07:27.980
that part of East Harlem
was only 100 years ago

00:07:27.980 --> 00:07:30.020
seen as the countryside.

00:07:30.020 --> 00:07:31.880
It's very funny.

00:07:31.880 --> 00:07:32.900
It was farmland.

00:07:32.900 --> 00:07:33.200
SHIH HUA LIONG: Right.

00:07:33.200 --> 00:07:33.890
It was upstate.

00:07:33.890 --> 00:07:35.098
DAVID ADJAYE: It was upstate.

00:07:35.098 --> 00:07:37.080
That's where you got
to get away from it all

00:07:37.080 --> 00:07:39.400
and now it's very much
the island and the city.

00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:41.270
And so we wanted to
kind of reference that.

00:07:41.270 --> 00:07:44.180
So we were referencing
the great bucolic idea

00:07:44.180 --> 00:07:45.897
of kind of flower gardens.

00:07:45.897 --> 00:07:48.230
and there were many flower
gardens up there at that time

00:07:48.230 --> 00:07:53.200
because Harlem is a Dutch word,
it was a Dutch colony actually,

00:07:53.200 --> 00:07:55.970
that sort of formed
that Upper Harlem.

00:07:55.970 --> 00:07:58.550
So I was very
fascinated by that,

00:07:58.550 --> 00:08:02.834
this idea of a kind of Dutch
farming sort of flowering

00:08:02.834 --> 00:08:03.500
kind of culture.

00:08:03.500 --> 00:08:06.170
So that's kind of embossed
in the architecture.

00:08:06.170 --> 00:08:09.710
But it's also where Duke
Ellington parked his car,

00:08:09.710 --> 00:08:11.900
it used to be a car
park there all the time.

00:08:11.900 --> 00:08:18.470
And the building has
about a 30% intake

00:08:18.470 --> 00:08:20.900
of musicians who, for
some strange reason,

00:08:20.900 --> 00:08:23.810
are probably the largest
group that become homeless.

00:08:23.810 --> 00:08:26.390
Because we see these kind
of successful musicians,

00:08:26.390 --> 00:08:28.470
but there are so many
that dedicate their lives

00:08:28.470 --> 00:08:32.210
and don't make it and sort of
don't have family, fall out

00:08:32.210 --> 00:08:34.789
of the social structure,
and end up on the street.

00:08:34.789 --> 00:08:39.620
And they're these incredibly
talented people who have just

00:08:39.620 --> 00:08:41.100
fallen off the edge of society.

00:08:41.100 --> 00:08:44.422
So it sort of was interesting
that the building is sort of

00:08:44.422 --> 00:08:46.130
filled with those
characters so we wanted

00:08:46.130 --> 00:08:48.939
to make spaces where they
could teach and support,

00:08:48.939 --> 00:08:50.480
that's part of the
buildings program,

00:08:50.480 --> 00:08:54.680
that they can mentor young
kids or do rich programs.

00:08:54.680 --> 00:08:57.260
There's a storytelling museum
that we put in because we also

00:08:57.260 --> 00:08:59.620
wanted to not have a
building like this not

00:08:59.620 --> 00:09:02.120
be near culture because it's
usually the furthest thing away

00:09:02.120 --> 00:09:04.650
for this community
to be near culture.

00:09:04.650 --> 00:09:07.220
So we brokered with the
city and with the sort

00:09:07.220 --> 00:09:09.180
of cultural
institutions to create

00:09:09.180 --> 00:09:12.480
a children's storytelling
museum in the building

00:09:12.480 --> 00:09:15.140
so that there's
continual life coming

00:09:15.140 --> 00:09:17.600
and the arts are
celebrated there.

00:09:17.600 --> 00:09:20.270
The performing arts
are there, that's

00:09:20.270 --> 00:09:22.874
a little bit of commercial
space but very, very little.

00:09:22.874 --> 00:09:24.290
SHIH HUA LIONG:
And the preschool.

00:09:24.290 --> 00:09:25.490
DAVID ADJAYE: And
there's the preschool,

00:09:25.490 --> 00:09:27.198
which is a very, very
important component

00:09:27.198 --> 00:09:29.660
to have very high quality
preschool offering

00:09:29.660 --> 00:09:30.999
right in the building.

00:09:30.999 --> 00:09:33.040
And the third part which,
is not fully activated,

00:09:33.040 --> 00:09:35.930
is that there's a kind
of farmer's market

00:09:35.930 --> 00:09:38.060
that kind of sometimes
comes to the plaza.

00:09:38.060 --> 00:09:40.730
But actually, we got
zoning from Amanda Burton

00:09:40.730 --> 00:09:43.487
