on the roof of the residents

00:09:43.487 --> 00:09:45.820
so they can have their own
allotments on the roof, which

00:09:45.820 --> 00:09:46.800
we're working on now.

00:09:46.800 --> 00:09:49.580
So really, the building is
a kind of a total ecology

00:09:49.580 --> 00:09:51.950
and really, these are
people who are just

00:09:51.950 --> 00:09:56.020
getting their first homes of
families are single people.

00:09:56.020 --> 00:09:58.130
And it's meant to
show that this can

00:09:58.130 --> 00:10:01.710
be a transmitory part and a kind
of dignified part of our city.

00:10:01.710 --> 00:10:04.586
It doesn't have to feel
like it's some negative.

00:10:04.586 --> 00:10:05.710
SHIH HUA LIONG: Absolutely.

00:10:05.710 --> 00:10:08.550
And you talk a lot about
some of the artists

00:10:08.550 --> 00:10:10.770
and you've worked
with a lot of artists.

00:10:10.770 --> 00:10:14.450
I know in Harlem, you're also
working on the Studio Museum.

00:10:14.450 --> 00:10:16.890
So tell us a little bit about
what that project entails

00:10:16.890 --> 00:10:19.339
and how it's going to sort of
transform that neighborhood.

00:10:19.339 --> 00:10:20.130
DAVID ADJAYE: Yeah.

00:10:20.130 --> 00:10:24.320
So where we were, the Sugar
Hill project is on a 155th,

00:10:24.320 --> 00:10:27.270
so up in sort of East Harlem.

00:10:27.270 --> 00:10:30.690
But the Studio Museum in
Harlem is really the beginning

00:10:30.690 --> 00:10:35.460
of the sort of black Renaissance
arts movement in the US,

00:10:35.460 --> 00:10:37.530
really sort of at the
moment of the civil rights

00:10:37.530 --> 00:10:38.850
kind of emancipation moment.

00:10:38.850 --> 00:10:42.870
So it's really their 50th
anniversary right now.

00:10:42.870 --> 00:10:45.270
And they were
basically an agency

00:10:45.270 --> 00:10:47.520
to deal with the
racism in the arts.

00:10:47.520 --> 00:10:51.750
It's really sort of secluded
a lot of white artists

00:10:51.750 --> 00:10:53.860
and sculptors from coming
into the mainstream

00:10:53.860 --> 00:10:57.880
because it just wasn't seen
to be what they should be--

00:10:57.880 --> 00:11:00.286
they weren't considered
part of the canon.

00:11:00.286 --> 00:11:02.160
So there were many
artists that were actually

00:11:02.160 --> 00:11:05.490
collaborating with
many white artists

00:11:05.490 --> 00:11:07.200
as young sort of practitioners.

00:11:07.200 --> 00:11:08.930
But then as their
careers blossomed,

00:11:08.930 --> 00:11:10.710
the black artists were
kind of left behind

00:11:10.710 --> 00:11:12.168
and the white
artists kind of rose.

00:11:12.168 --> 00:11:13.800
And intellectually,
there was a lot

00:11:13.800 --> 00:11:17.417
of kind of fertile sort of
relationship between these two

00:11:17.417 --> 00:11:18.000
organizations.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:20.724
As And so the Studio Museum
was born to kind of collect

00:11:20.724 --> 00:11:22.140
this group and not
to let them get

00:11:22.140 --> 00:11:25.380
lost and to also make
sure that there was agency

00:11:25.380 --> 00:11:27.620
and support for this community.

00:11:27.620 --> 00:11:30.210
So it started off very
much as a very low budget

00:11:30.210 --> 00:11:32.700
thing, just very simple spaces.

00:11:32.700 --> 00:11:36.180
Then they got the building
on 125th through the city,

00:11:36.180 --> 00:11:38.580
brokering a deal with them
to give them a cheap rent.

00:11:38.580 --> 00:11:41.250
And then Max Bond,
an amazing architect,

00:11:41.250 --> 00:11:44.260
refurbished it and created three
very large rooms to show work.

00:11:44.260 --> 00:11:48.750
And more or less, that was
maybe in the sort of '60s

00:11:48.750 --> 00:11:50.580
and that has lasted till now.

00:11:50.580 --> 00:11:52.080
And space has been
falling apart.

00:11:52.080 --> 00:11:56.820
But last year there was a
big competition in the city

00:11:56.820 --> 00:11:57.820
and internationally.

00:11:57.820 --> 00:12:00.020
We won the competition
to rebuild it.

00:12:00.020 --> 00:12:03.840
And the idea is to really
turn it into the premier arts

00:12:03.840 --> 00:12:08.430
destination in the north of
the city, so away sort of

00:12:08.430 --> 00:12:12.900
off the Museum Mile, but up on
125th, very close to Apollo.

00:12:12.900 --> 00:12:16.950
And really, 125th is
changing dramatically.

00:12:16.950 --> 00:12:20.910
But it's lot of commercial
sort of business is coming

00:12:20.910 --> 00:12:23.000
and there's very little
cultural anchors.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:26.016
So places like the Apollo,
places like the Studio Museum

00:12:26.016 --> 00:12:27.390
become very
important to the city

00:12:27.390 --> 00:12:30.460
because the anchor a
certain continuity.

00:12:30.460 --> 00:12:33.750
So we are making a building
which tries to create in a way

00:12:33.750 --> 00:12:36.230
that the Whitney
created something

00:12:36.230 --> 00:12:40.786
in '77, a cultural anchor,
that could have just

00:12:40.786 --> 00:12:42.660
become a kind of
residential area completely.

00:12:42.660 --> 00:12:45.240
But that cultural
anchor defined the way

00:12:45.240 --> 00:12:46.800
in which that center works.

00:12:46.800 --> 00:12:50.730
We're hoping that by creating
a significant cultural offering

00:12:50.730 --> 00:12:54.935
of exhibition spaces, lecture
spaces, public engagement

00:12:54.935 --> 00:12:57.060
education kind of programs
which are very important

00:12:57.060 --> 00:12:59.059
and studios for artists,
what they became famous

00:12:59.059 --> 00:13:02.490
for is that they incubated
artists and gave them

00:13:02.490 --> 00:13:05.190
a year or two years'
studio space to perfect

00:13:05.190 --> 00:13:08.249
their work as residents.

00:13:08.249 --> 00:13:09.915
And so that program
will still continue,

00:13:09.915 --> 00:13:11.790
so there will be
artist-in-residence programs

00:13:11.790 --> 00:13:12.910
still going on there.

00:13:12.910 --> 00:13:15.190
And this will become a kind
of major arts destination

00:13:15.190 --> 00:13:16.100
on 125th.

00:13:16.100 --> 00:13:20.280
And we're working with the city,
sort of quite a way into it,

00:13:20.280 --> 00:13:21.960
we'll be starting
on site next year

00:13:21.960 --> 00:13:24.168
to really build this very
significant building, which

00:13:24.168 --> 00:13:26.320
will hopefully create
an anchor on 125th

00:13:26.320 --> 00:13:29.757
and then carry the story on in a
kind of much more powerful way.

00:13:29.757 --> 00:13:30.840
SHIH HUA LIONG: Wonderful.

00:13:30.840 --> 00:13:32.490
We look forward to
seeing that in New York.

00:13:32.490 --> 00:13:34.666
DAVID ADJAYE: I think they're
releasing images in the fall.

00:13:34.666 --> 00:13:35.749
SHIH HUA LIONG: Oh, great.

00:13:35.749 --> 00:13:40.170
So we talked about sort of
social housing, the arts.

00:13:40.170 --> 00:13:42.810
I want to sort of turn
the focus a little bit

00:13:42.810 --> 00:13:47.340
on libraries and
access to information.

00:13:47.340 --> 00:13:49.110
Libraries have
really become the--

00:13:49.110 --> 00:13:51.920
well, used to really
be the focal point

00:13:51.920 --> 00:13:53.910
of a community for information.

00:13:53.910 --> 00:13:57.330
I know you've worked on the
libraries in the UK, the two

00:13:57.330 --> 00:13:58.040
ideas.

00:13:58.040 --> 00:13:59.377
DAVID ADJAYE: [INAUDIBLE], yes.

00:13:59.377 --> 00:14:01.710
SHIH HUA LIONG: Tell us about
the challenges around that

00:14:01.710 --> 00:14:04.250
and how you've been able
to sort of transform.

00:14:04.250 --> 00:14:05.190
DAVID ADJAYE: Yeah.

00:14:05.190 --> 00:14:08.597
Well, it's interesting
because the two projects

00:14:08.597 --> 00:14:10.680
that I won really at the
beginning my career, sort

00:14:10.680 --> 00:14:14.430
of 2002, were at that moment
when the internet really

00:14:14.430 --> 00:14:17.650
was becoming something that
was clearly going to change

00:14:17.650 --> 00:14:21.000
our world or our
lives and was starting

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:24.870
to impact the typology
of certain institutions

00:14:24.870 --> 00:14:25.530
like libraries.

00:14:25.530 --> 00:14:27.030
And so there was a
lot of discussion

00:14:27.030 --> 00:14:28.140
at that time and everybody
said, well, libraries

00:14:28.140 --> 00:14:29.070
are going to disappear
and everything's

00:14:29.070 --> 00:14:30.390
going to be on their laptops.

00:14:30.390 --> 00:14:32.580
And to a certain extent,
it's completely changed,

00:14:32.580 --> 00:14:34.450
but libraries
haven't disappeared.

00:14:34.450 --> 00:14:37.410
But they have completely changed
because in a way, if you think

00:14:37.410 --> 00:14:39.090
about the library,
we think of libraries

00:14:39.090 --> 00:14:40.590
sort of in a romantic
sense in terms

00:14:40.590 --> 00:14:42.330
of academic and
historical libraries.

00:14:42.330 --> 00:14:45.750
But libraries for normal
people, citizens in the city,

00:14:45.750 --> 00:14:49.155
really happened post-war in
almost all Western cities.

00:14:49.155 --> 00:14:51.780
It really was after the war that
there was a systematic program

00:14:51.780 --> 00:14:55.650
to make boxes with books,
and usually a certain amount

00:14:55.650 --> 00:14:58.376
of books which gave you a
sort of body of knowledge.

00:14:58.376 --> 00:15:00.750
And that was the way in which
every suburb had something,

00:15:00.750 --> 00:15:03.150
and that was the first thing
out of libraries outside

00:15:03.150 --> 00:15:08.282
of the university or the kind
of great sort of institutions.

00:15:08.282 --> 00:15:09.990
So it's really a modern
typology, but one

00:15:09.990 --> 00:15:11.727
that very quickly became--

00:15:11.727 --> 00:15:12.810
SHIH HUA LIONG: Died down.

00:15:12.810 --> 00:15:13.580
DAVID ADJAYE: Yeah, died down.

00:15:13.580 --> 00:15:14.080
It shrunk.

00:15:14.080 --> 00:15:15.660
But also it became
something that

00:15:15.660 --> 00:15:18.720
became a very important way
for families and communities

00:15:18.720 --> 00:15:21.750
to have access to
the sort of-- it

00:15:21.750 --> 00:15:25.149
became a first device to
democratize knowledge, really.

00:15:25.149 --> 00:15:26.940
But in doing that, also
what it did-- apart

00:15:26.940 --> 00:15:28.398
from just democratizing
knowledge--

00:15:28.398 --> 00:15:31.470
it also became a
multigenerational institution

00:15:31.470 --> 00:15:33.660
for communities.

00:15:33.660 --> 00:15:36.060
Because as communities,
we basically

00:15:36.060 --> 00:15:39.240
stay away from different
generations naturally.

00:15:39.240 --> 00:15:42.090
We stay with our
tribes, our age groups.

00:15:42.090 --> 00:15:44.086
And places like
libraries are actually

00:15:44.086 --> 00:15:45.960
one of the few places
where multi-generations

00:15:45.960 --> 00:15:46.340
come together.

00:15:46.340 --> 00:15:47.820
You see young kids,
you see teens,

00:15:47.820 --> 00:15:50.370
you see toddlers,
grandma and grandpa.

00:15:50.370 --> 00:15:52.410
And actually, what
we've all realized

00:15:52.410 --> 00:15:54.750
is that these are really
powerful social incubating

00:15:54.750 --> 00:15:55.840
spaces.

00:15:55.840 --> 00:15:57.540
So the competition
entry was to say

00:15:57.540 --> 00:16:01.469
that the library, yes in terms
of the information has shifted,

00:16:01.469 --> 00:16:03.510
but actually the idea of
that kind of destination

00:16:03.510 --> 00:16:05.570
in the community that
brings multi-generations

00:16:05.570 --> 00:16:07.920
together is even more
necessary in a world

00:16:07.920 --> 00:16:11.220
where we are now tapped into
things and in a world where

00:16:11.220 --> 00:16:14.190
things are very expensive
for certain families

00:16:14.190 --> 00:16:17.205
and our kind of notion of the
unit of the family structure

00:16:17.205 --> 00:16:17.770
has changed.

00:16:17.770 --> 00:16:18.900
The library has to do more.

00:16:18.900 --> 00:16:22.290
It has to become a place
where maybe a single parent

00:16:22.290 --> 00:16:25.540
family can allow their kids
to stay till 11 o'clock,

00:16:25.540 --> 00:16:30.030
not just open as a kind of nine
to five or nine till seven.

00:16:30.030 --> 00:16:32.400
It has to kind of offer
language classes maybe

00:16:32.400 --> 00:16:36.090
or motor mechanics
or learning massage,

00:16:36.090 --> 00:16:38.680
it has to offer computer skills.

00:16:38.680 --> 00:16:40.116
So actually, what
it started to do

00:16:40.116 --> 00:16:41.490
was it started to
melt what we're

00:16:41.490 --> 00:16:44.700
calling lifelong learning
with library services

00:16:44.700 --> 00:16:46.560
and the notion of
a community center.

00:16:46.560 --> 00:16:48.660
And so the libraries
that you're seeing now,

00:16:48.660 --> 00:16:52.110
we prototyped those
two at that time

00:16:52.110 --> 00:16:53.610
and we won a lot
of awards for it

00:16:53.610 --> 00:16:55.055
and started talking about it.

00:16:55.055 --> 00:16:57.180
And there have been a lot
of big signature projects

00:16:57.180 --> 00:17:00.810
that were done, but those
were the first to community

00:17:00.810 --> 00:17:03.526
sort of transformations that
really showed the library

00:17:03.526 --> 00:17:04.650
world that they could work.

00:17:04.650 --> 00:17:06.210
And it suddenly just
mushroomed around the world.

00:17:06.210 --> 00:17:08.970
We had all these library people
coming to London to learn

00:17:08.970 --> 00:17:11.068
and it's really had
this incredible effect

00:17:11.068 --> 00:17:11.859
all over the world.

00:17:11.859 --> 00:17:15.569
And I was also then brought
sort of almost a decade later

00:17:15.569 --> 00:17:20.119
to Washington to also then
kickstart their program when

00:17:20.119 --> 00:17:23.160
then Mayor Anthony Williams came
to London to see the libraries,

00:17:23.160 --> 00:17:25.990
called me, and wanted me to
go talk to his library team.

00:17:25.990 --> 00:17:29.090
And we built two libraries
in Washington, as well.

00:17:29.090 --> 00:17:32.190
And it was, again, helping
them understand this model

00:17:32.190 --> 00:17:34.320
and really bring
that into making

00:17:34.320 --> 00:17:36.870
a kind of signature
building which becomes

00:17:36.870 --> 00:17:38.100
an important community hub.

00:17:38.100 --> 00:17:39.790
And it's amazing when we
opened these buildings,

00:17:39.790 --> 00:17:41.498
people thought, oh,
nobody's going to go.

00:17:41.498 --> 00:17:45.040
They're so full,
they're oversubscribed

00:17:45.040 --> 00:17:48.207
and people are being pushed
out when they want to close.

00:17:48.207 --> 00:17:49.290
It's actually the reverse.

00:17:49.290 --> 00:17:52.260
We realized that actually
with the kind of accessibility

00:17:52.260 --> 00:17:55.260
we have, we also now crave
sort of powerful spaces

00:17:55.260 --> 00:17:57.710
that allow us to have
a kind of social life

00:17:57.710 --> 00:17:59.490
that's meaningful
beyond a retail mall

00:17:59.490 --> 00:18:01.184
or street, sidewalk.

00:18:01.184 --> 00:18:02.100
SHIH HUA LIONG: Right.

00:18:02.100 --> 00:18:04.290
And you talk about how
the library has also

00:18:04.290 --> 00:18:06.540
started to attract
sort of teenagers,

00:18:06.540 --> 00:18:10.590
where it's the spot to go to
is let's meet at the library.

00:18:10.590 --> 00:18:14.040
DAVID ADJAYE: That was actually
our benchmark of success.

00:18:14.040 --> 00:18:16.920
We said if we could
attract young teenagers

00:18:16.920 --> 00:18:20.306
to meet in the library,
rather than at a retail mall,

00:18:20.306 --> 00:18:21.180
then we were winning.

00:18:21.180 --> 00:18:22.080
SHIH HUA LIONG: Absolutely.

00:18:22.080 --> 00:18:23.580
DAVID ADJAYE: And
that was the test,

00:18:23.580 --> 00:18:26.220
and thankfully it did happen.

00:18:26.220 --> 00:18:29.430
SHIH HUA LIONG: So I'm glad
you mentioned Washington.

00:18:29.430 --> 00:18:33.390
With your significant
sort of signature project

00:18:33.390 --> 00:18:36.050
there, I'm sure
the audience also

00:18:36.050 --> 00:18:41.580
love to hear about just the
process of how you started

00:18:41.580 --> 00:18:45.480
the project, also the
significance of the crown

00:18:45.480 --> 00:18:49.480
at the National History
of African-American

00:18:49.480 --> 00:18:51.616
Culture and History.

00:18:51.616 --> 00:18:55.770
DAVID ADJAYE: Well, that museum
is really a project sort of I

00:18:55.770 --> 00:19:02.220
guess 200 years in the making,
philosophically, and 20 years

00:19:02.220 --> 00:19:03.880
to really bring to fruition.

00:19:03.880 --> 00:19:07.140
And it's the last possible
site on the monumental core

00:19:07.140 --> 00:19:09.800
of Washington.

00:19:09.800 --> 00:19:12.330
The Mall is divided into two
sections, if you don't know it.

00:19:12.330 --> 00:19:15.480
It's basically the museums
that go up to the Capitol

00:19:15.480 --> 00:19:19.840
from 15th and
Constitution Drive.

00:19:19.840 --> 00:19:22.710
If you don't know DC,
it's basically a cruciform

00:19:22.710 --> 00:19:25.650
and one part of the cruciform is
very strict, very French, very

00:19:25.650 --> 00:19:27.345
ordered with lots of museums.

00:19:30.094 --> 00:19:32.010
The Science and History
Museum is there, there

00:19:32.010 --> 00:19:35.100
sort of Hirshhorn is there,
the Smithsonian Castle,

00:19:35.100 --> 00:19:36.797
the American Museum et cetera.

00:19:36.797 --> 00:19:38.880
And then on the other side,
you have the monuments

00:19:38.880 --> 00:19:43.330
of the nation and it's much more
in a kind of English landscape.

00:19:43.330 --> 00:19:45.180
And it's taken 200
years to build this.

00:19:45.180 --> 00:19:46.721
And actually, when
the plan was made,

00:19:46.721 --> 00:19:49.107
there was a kind of petition
to have a museum that

00:19:49.107 --> 00:19:50.940
talked about the
African-American experience

00:19:50.940 --> 00:19:52.800
and its contribution
to America, but it

00:19:52.800 --> 00:19:55.270
was dismissed as not relevant.

00:19:55.270 --> 00:19:58.170
And so it's the
last building that

00:19:58.170 --> 00:20:00.660
can possibly be built on the
Mall in terms of its master

00:20:00.660 --> 00:20:01.710
plan.

00:20:01.710 --> 00:20:03.880
All the institutional
buildings have been built

00:20:03.880 --> 00:20:05.160
and the monuments are full.

00:20:05.160 --> 00:20:07.650
They have to find places to
make new monuments, which

00:20:07.650 --> 00:20:09.750
is why the Vietnam
Memorial is so powerful.

00:20:09.750 --> 00:20:13.900
It was kind of discovering
a new way of doing it.

00:20:13.900 --> 00:20:16.426
And we've just
completed the last site,

00:20:16.426 --> 00:20:18.300
which seemed like the
worst site because it's

00:20:18.300 --> 00:20:20.662
half the size of all
the other museums.

00:20:20.662 --> 00:20:22.620
But in a way, the position
of it is so powerful

00:20:22.620 --> 00:20:24.300
that it allowed
us to do something

00:20:24.300 --> 00:20:27.870
that maybe we couldn't have
done if we had a different site.

00:20:27.870 --> 00:20:30.330
So the museum is
really trying to talk

00:20:30.330 --> 00:20:37.560
about the story of the
African-American sort narrative

00:20:37.560 --> 00:20:42.400
from really the Declaration of
Independence, the declaration

00:20:42.400 --> 00:20:44.760
of emancipation to now.

00:20:44.760 --> 00:20:47.370
So really, there's a kind of
journey from the 14th century,

00:20:47.370 --> 00:20:50.280
so there's a kind of moment
to think about the impact

00:20:50.280 --> 00:20:52.710
of slavery and the kind of
commercialization of human

00:20:52.710 --> 00:20:56.550
trade and how America's
foundations are in that,

00:20:56.550 --> 00:20:58.950
but then really how this
community evolves out of that

00:20:58.950 --> 00:21:04.830
kind of trauma, moved through
incredible movements which

00:21:04.830 --> 00:21:07.660
shift the legislation and
the mood of this country--

00:21:07.660 --> 00:21:10.660
and it's ongoing, as we know--

00:21:10.660 --> 00:21:12.960
and how that really
allows you to understand

00:21:12.960 --> 00:21:15.420
the identity of the
African-American here

00:21:15.420 --> 00:21:18.130
but also to understand
the identity of America.

00:21:18.130 --> 00:21:19.847
It's not just a museum
for the community,

00:21:19.847 --> 00:21:21.430
it's actually an
American museum which

00:21:21.430 --> 00:21:23.910
really helps you to
understand fundamentally

00:21:23.910 --> 00:21:26.100
how America is made.

00:21:26.100 --> 00:21:28.110
And its narrative for
us was that it really

00:21:28.110 --> 00:21:30.270
also cements the
relationship between Africa

00:21:30.270 --> 00:21:31.560
and the Americas.

00:21:31.560 --> 00:21:34.351
Because by the slave
trade, you have

00:21:34.351 --> 00:21:35.850
this kind of
incredible relationship

00:21:35.850 --> 00:21:37.464
that is sort of formed.

00:21:37.464 --> 00:21:38.880
And so we said
that we didn't want

00:21:38.880 --> 00:21:40.140
to just make a museum
which is maybe just

00:21:40.140 --> 00:21:41.765
to make a kind of
Greek temple and then

00:21:41.765 --> 00:21:45.035
fill it with artifacts or a
palace or a fabulous building.

00:21:45.035 --> 00:21:47.160
We thought that with this
building in being so late

00:21:47.160 --> 00:21:49.440
but being so important
should really

00:21:49.440 --> 00:21:53.150
be from its very silhouette be
a narrative about the story.

00:21:53.150 --> 00:21:55.890
So in a way, it
contributes both in terms

00:21:55.890 --> 00:21:59.130
of its aura in its
landscape as a monument,

00:21:59.130 --> 00:22:02.940
but also then as a museum
educating in its content.

00:22:02.940 --> 00:22:06.240
And that kind of very decision
was what distinguished us

00:22:06.240 --> 00:22:09.450
from our peers because
we were able to present

00:22:09.450 --> 00:22:13.500
a narrative about how you make
form, which was about speaking

00:22:13.500 --> 00:22:15.960
from the silhouette
to the very smallest

00:22:15.960 --> 00:22:18.780
thing inside the building,
that everything is kind of part

00:22:18.780 --> 00:22:21.420
of the content of
understanding this narrative,

00:22:21.420 --> 00:22:23.599
everything is asking
you questions.

00:22:23.599 --> 00:22:25.890
So when we opened the building,
people were like, well,

00:22:25.890 --> 00:22:26.590
what is this?

00:22:26.590 --> 00:22:29.250
And so the storytelling
started then.

00:22:29.250 --> 00:22:35.550
It's inspired by
Benin caryatid shrine

00:22:35.550 --> 00:22:38.700
structures in West Africa.

00:22:38.700 --> 00:22:40.260
Why?

00:22:40.260 --> 00:22:43.410
A large part of the
community comes from there.

00:22:43.410 --> 00:22:46.600
Because it was commercial trade,
it was meticulously documented,

00:22:46.600 --> 00:22:47.640
shockingly.

00:22:47.640 --> 00:22:50.580
No data about people's
names or tribes or anything,

00:22:50.580 --> 00:22:51.870
but the content--

00:22:51.870 --> 00:22:52.680
the ships' cargo.

00:22:52.680 --> 00:22:54.690
So we know where
the ships came from

00:22:54.690 --> 00:22:56.580
and what they did,
so we know the areas.

00:22:56.580 --> 00:23:01.490
And so we made a fiction about
that time, the 14th century,

00:23:01.490 --> 00:23:03.240
what would be the great
things that people

00:23:03.240 --> 00:23:05.550
would know about from
west and central Africa?

00:23:05.550 --> 00:23:08.892
And they would all know
about the Yoruba of Benin

00:23:08.892 --> 00:23:10.600
because they were the
greatest craftsmen.

00:23:10.600 --> 00:23:12.330
They were the Greeks
of Europe, so they

00:23:12.330 --> 00:23:15.390
were the Greeks of west Africa.

00:23:15.390 --> 00:23:18.870
They were the best casters,
the best woodworkers,

00:23:18.870 --> 00:23:22.200
and the employers or the courts
and empires that were around.

00:23:22.200 --> 00:23:23.850
There was a lot
of intermarrying.

00:23:23.850 --> 00:23:26.100
So we said, well, OK,
let's look at the best

00:23:26.100 --> 00:23:27.870
arts from that
place and let's see

00:23:27.870 --> 00:23:29.580
if we can use that as
a reference to say,

00:23:29.580 --> 00:23:31.746
this would be one of the
kind of high points of kind

00:23:31.746 --> 00:23:35.840
of an artistic kind of moment
that would be a memory.

00:23:35.840 --> 00:23:37.590
And then let's kind
of create a hybridity,

00:23:37.590 --> 00:23:40.020
which is the African-American
experience between Africa

00:23:40.020 --> 00:23:43.620
and America, but then talking
about the experience of then

00:23:43.620 --> 00:23:46.890
sort of coming from the roots
of the South, the agrarian

00:23:46.890 --> 00:23:50.600
landscape, working the land,
building the infrastructure

00:23:50.600 --> 00:23:52.290
of the country, labor.

00:23:52.290 --> 00:23:54.000
And we wanted to look
at sort of the kind

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:57.660
of beautiful traditions of
ironworking, ironsmithing,

00:23:57.660 --> 00:23:59.370
which was something
that a lot of--

00:23:59.370 --> 00:24:03.927
if you weren't in the military
or a carpenter or on the field,

00:24:03.927 --> 00:24:05.760
ironsmithing was a very
important labor that

00:24:05.760 --> 00:24:07.680
actually built a lot of South--

00:24:07.680 --> 00:24:10.080
railway buildings, et cetera.

00:24:10.080 --> 00:24:12.450
And a lot of
African-American slaves

00:24:12.450 --> 00:24:15.000
in kind of their first sort
of when they became free

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:16.995
went into artsmithing as trades.

00:24:16.995 --> 00:24:18.120
So we wanted to honor that.

00:24:18.120 --> 00:24:19.620
We particularly
looked at somebody

00:24:19.620 --> 00:24:23.400
from Charleston who now is
becoming very well-known as one

00:24:23.400 --> 00:24:27.120
of the kind of great ironsmiths
of his time, Philip Simmons.

00:24:27.120 --> 00:24:29.460
And I took one of
his metal ironworks

00:24:29.460 --> 00:24:34.710
and sort of mapped it
and created a screen

00:24:34.710 --> 00:24:38.124
from the mapping,
literally, to create

00:24:38.124 --> 00:24:40.040
sort of what looks like
an ornamental pattern.

00:24:40.040 --> 00:24:41.610
But it's actually
really a redrawing

00:24:41.610 --> 00:24:44.790
of this man's work
as a kind of way

00:24:44.790 --> 00:24:49.320
to hybridize the corona form and
to create the nature of labor

00:24:49.320 --> 00:24:52.030
in the kind of detail
of the building.

00:24:52.030 --> 00:24:54.230
So that became a kind
of way to kind of make

00:24:54.230 --> 00:24:56.280
kind of a very
complicated skin which

00:24:56.280 --> 00:24:57.600
is environmentally responsive.

00:24:57.600 --> 00:24:59.860
We're the first gold LEEDs
building on the Mall.

00:24:59.860 --> 00:25:03.090
I know it's shocking, but
we recollect our water,

00:25:03.090 --> 00:25:04.247
we're sustainable.

00:25:04.247 --> 00:25:06.080
And then really because
the building concept

00:25:06.080 --> 00:25:09.390
was to put 50% of the
building underground

00:25:09.390 --> 00:25:11.870
and then to create two
special chambers up above

00:25:11.870 --> 00:25:15.270
and to create a narrative
where you go down 80 feet

00:25:15.270 --> 00:25:18.380
and then you rise up, which is
not a normal museum narrative.

00:25:18.380 --> 00:25:20.060
In fact, all the
museum people said,

00:25:20.060 --> 00:25:23.410
this will never work because
you should go into a lobby,

00:25:23.410 --> 00:25:26.990
it should be grand, and then
you go into rooms like the Met.

00:25:26.990 --> 00:25:27.890
And we said, no.

00:25:27.890 --> 00:25:29.140
SHIH HUA LIONG: Rethinking it.

00:25:29.140 --> 00:25:30.560
DAVID ADJAYE: Yeah.

00:25:30.560 --> 00:25:32.270
So we rethought
this and in a way,

00:25:32.270 --> 00:25:34.340
we buried history in the ground.

00:25:34.340 --> 00:25:37.820
And then we talked about
the first professional class

00:25:37.820 --> 00:25:39.880
being in the upper
level and then

00:25:39.880 --> 00:25:43.290
the sort of performing arts and
entertainment being above that.

00:25:43.290 --> 00:25:45.500
And then we created also
the end of the project

00:25:45.500 --> 00:25:49.370
to draw people the best view
of the entire Mall at the top,

00:25:49.370 --> 00:25:51.137
where you have a
window which gives

00:25:51.137 --> 00:25:52.970
you views all the way
to Arlington and right

00:25:52.970 --> 00:25:53.595
to the Capitol.

00:25:53.595 --> 00:25:55.136
And it's the only
place where you can

00:25:55.136 --> 00:25:56.349
get this incredible overview.

00:25:56.349 --> 00:25:57.890
So we turned the
building into a sort

00:25:57.890 --> 00:26:00.890
of bit of a sort of a
tower, a ziggurat, that you

00:26:00.890 --> 00:26:03.440
sort of climb, a journey
that you go from the ground

00:26:03.440 --> 00:26:04.310
up to the top.

00:26:04.310 --> 00:26:06.320
And in doing the
work, our instincts

00:26:06.320 --> 00:26:09.851
were sort of proven right
because we placed it

00:26:09.851 --> 00:26:11.600
in the ground and there
was a slave market

00:26:11.600 --> 00:26:13.850
just behind the White
House on this site, which

00:26:13.850 --> 00:26:16.400
was astonishing when we
find out the history.

00:26:16.400 --> 00:26:19.442
So we sort of in a way
by not building on one

00:26:19.442 --> 00:26:20.900
sit e putting things
underneath it,

00:26:20.900 --> 00:26:23.850
we sort of kept the kind
of sacred relationship

00:26:23.850 --> 00:26:25.971
to that land.

00:26:25.971 --> 00:26:28.220
It's a place where everybody
arrives on the north side

00:26:28.220 --> 00:26:30.460
and waits and there's
a kind of water pool

00:26:30.460 --> 00:26:32.180
that just kind of
celebrates that idea.

00:26:32.180 --> 00:26:33.870
So the building is
full of narratives.

00:26:33.870 --> 00:26:35.828
We could keep talking
about it for a long time,

00:26:35.828 --> 00:26:39.005
but it's something that I would
encourage people to experience.

00:26:39.005 --> 00:26:40.130
SHIH HUA LIONG: Definitely.

00:26:40.130 --> 00:26:41.606
Thank you for sharing that.

00:26:41.606 --> 00:26:42.980
I'll just cover
one more question

00:26:42.980 --> 00:26:45.460
and we can open it
up to the audience.

00:26:45.460 --> 00:26:47.510
So you were born
in Africa, you've

00:26:47.510 --> 00:26:49.820
lived there for a long time,
you're doing a lot of work

00:26:49.820 --> 00:26:50.600
there.

00:26:50.600 --> 00:26:53.480
Tell us about what key
projects are happening in

00:26:53.480 --> 00:26:56.960
Africa and perhaps some of the
challenges in working there.

00:26:56.960 --> 00:26:58.880
DAVID ADJAYE: Challenges,
there are a lot.

00:26:58.880 --> 00:27:02.660
So there's a kind of second
wave of a sense of kind

00:27:02.660 --> 00:27:06.560
of developed, especially
in central and west Africa,

00:27:06.560 --> 00:27:09.680
and also in east Africa
now, and their governments

00:27:09.680 --> 00:27:12.430
are trying to deal
with very difficult--

00:27:12.430 --> 00:27:15.071
these are nations that
are only 50 years old.

00:27:15.071 --> 00:27:16.820
We think of Africa
with its great history,

00:27:16.820 --> 00:27:18.903
but in terms of its modern
history, its modernity,

00:27:18.903 --> 00:27:20.149
it's really new.

00:27:20.149 --> 00:27:22.190
And just as the civil
rights were happening here,

00:27:22.190 --> 00:27:24.110
that's when actually African
independence was happening

00:27:24.110 --> 00:27:26.280
and kind of new identities
were being formed.

00:27:26.280 --> 00:27:28.092
So the first wave
was very interesting,

00:27:28.092 --> 00:27:30.550
people like [INAUDIBLE] building
incredible infrastructure,

00:27:30.550 --> 00:27:31.190
et cetera.

00:27:31.190 --> 00:27:34.190
But really, it pitted
out and got quite a lot

00:27:34.190 --> 00:27:39.320
of problems in terms of
power and opportunity,

00:27:39.320 --> 00:27:42.650
all the sort of things
that beginning states have.

00:27:42.650 --> 00:27:44.120
But there is a kind
of movement now

00:27:44.120 --> 00:27:46.250
where economies are
getting more robust,

00:27:46.250 --> 00:27:48.250
people are starting to
learn how to kind of work

00:27:48.250 --> 00:27:49.365
within a globalized world.

00:27:49.365 --> 00:27:51.740
And certain leaders now have
understood that architecture

00:27:51.740 --> 00:27:54.710
is very much part of that, that
architecture and infrastructure

00:27:54.710 --> 00:27:56.780
have to be brought together.

00:27:56.780 --> 00:27:59.780
So I'm working for the Ghanian
government right now helping

00:27:59.780 --> 00:28:01.700
to develop their
rail infrastructure

00:28:01.700 --> 00:28:05.980
system for the country, talking
about nodal sort of points

00:28:05.980 --> 00:28:08.270
and how we develop
terminals that

00:28:08.270 --> 00:28:11.260
celebrate sort of civic life.

00:28:11.260 --> 00:28:14.060
In Dakar, I'm working
with the World Bank

00:28:14.060 --> 00:28:16.939
to kind of put their
infrastructure directly

00:28:16.939 --> 00:28:18.980
in the continent and not
just have it in America,

00:28:18.980 --> 00:28:22.190
but to have it on the ground
so that the countries that

00:28:22.190 --> 00:28:25.940
are being served actually
have a kind of base there.

00:28:25.940 --> 00:28:28.226
In places like Gabon, I'm
helping the government maser

00:28:28.226 --> 00:28:31.646
of the campus to kind of have
a much more smart government

00:28:31.646 --> 00:28:34.020
campus where people can find
things and relate to things.

00:28:34.020 --> 00:28:35.769
So it's like these are
fundamental things,

00:28:35.769 --> 00:28:37.670
but these are
nation-building things

00:28:37.670 --> 00:28:39.530
that are really
fascinating to me, as well.

00:28:39.530 --> 00:28:43.597
So that's why I have an office
and Accra to deal with that.

00:28:43.597 --> 00:28:45.180
SHIH HUA LIONG: And
we talked about it

00:28:45.180 --> 00:28:48.520
earlier this afternoon,
how working in Africa,

00:28:48.520 --> 00:28:51.680
working with governments
now is sort of really

00:28:51.680 --> 00:28:55.550
at the core, right, of
who you are and sort

00:28:55.550 --> 00:29:00.140
of your vision of sort of civic
experience and transformation.

00:29:00.140 --> 00:29:02.360
DAVID ADJAYE: It feels
very privileged to be

00:29:02.360 --> 00:29:04.380
able to have that
opportunity because I mean,

00:29:04.380 --> 00:29:09.920
my work in London and in New
York has generally tended to be

00:29:09.920 --> 00:29:11.300
much more the private sector.

00:29:11.300 --> 00:29:14.840
But now in London also, I'm now
the mayor's design advocate,

00:29:14.840 --> 00:29:18.590
so I'm now sort of supporting
in a political role

00:29:18.590 --> 00:29:21.500
the shaping of the city and
the next sort of iteration

00:29:21.500 --> 00:29:25.047
of the mayor's sort of time.

00:29:25.047 --> 00:29:26.630
So that would be
much more into a kind

00:29:26.630 --> 00:29:29.840
of philosophical realm of how
London is going to develop.

00:29:29.840 --> 00:29:34.670
But in the US, it's been working
with cultural institutions,

00:29:34.670 --> 00:29:37.400
but in a sense
private [INAUDIBLE]..

00:29:37.400 --> 00:29:42.860
So to suddenly go full steam
into more the political realm

00:29:42.860 --> 00:29:43.529
feels daunting.

00:29:43.529 --> 00:29:46.070
It's felt very daunting to start
off with because it's really

00:29:46.070 --> 00:29:48.920
something we're not trained to
do, so the logistics of that

00:29:48.920 --> 00:29:52.280
have been a quick a very
steep learning curve.

00:29:52.280 --> 00:29:56.450
But what they create from us is
the way we think and the way we

00:29:56.450 --> 00:29:57.200
problem-solve.

00:29:57.200 --> 00:30:01.160
I would say aesthetics come
from the problem-solving.

00:30:01.160 --> 00:30:04.470
We are obsessed with
aesthetics, but we're

00:30:04.470 --> 00:30:08.340
obsessed with aesthetics as a
solution to problem-solving.

00:30:08.340 --> 00:30:10.710
So I always say to my
team, we solve the problem

00:30:10.710 --> 00:30:12.490
and then derive the
aesthetics out of it.

00:30:12.490 --> 00:30:14.750
We don't create the aesthetics
and try and solve the problem.

00:30:14.750 --> 00:30:15.450
SHIH HUA LIONG: Absolutely.

00:30:15.450 --> 00:30:15.950
Great.

00:30:15.950 --> 00:30:17.670
Thank you.

00:30:17.670 --> 00:30:19.170
And the other thing
I told you about

00:30:19.170 --> 00:30:22.470
was the best part of the
talks is really opening it up

00:30:22.470 --> 00:30:23.800
to the audience.

00:30:23.800 --> 00:30:26.912
So would you like to start
and introduce yourself?

00:30:26.912 --> 00:30:28.120
AUDIENCE: My name is Florian.

00:30:28.120 --> 00:30:29.494
It's super cool
that you're here,

00:30:29.494 --> 00:30:31.265
so thanks for making time.

00:30:31.265 --> 00:30:32.140
I have two questions.

00:30:32.140 --> 00:30:35.490
The first is as you
talked about storytelling,

00:30:35.490 --> 00:30:38.970
I recently watched
Chimamanda Adichie's Ted talk

00:30:38.970 --> 00:30:40.890
about single
narrative and I know

00:30:40.890 --> 00:30:44.162
that she talks about how
collectively Africa, right,

00:30:44.162 --> 00:30:45.120
has suffered from this.

00:30:45.120 --> 00:30:47.286
And I think we see a lot
of that narrative in the US

00:30:47.286 --> 00:30:49.980
around our black
population here.

00:30:49.980 --> 00:30:52.950
Your work at the Smithsonian
is in many ways centered

00:30:52.950 --> 00:30:56.310
on creating a second
narrative, right,

00:30:56.310 --> 00:30:58.260
but that's not the work
