00:34:34.596 --> 00:34:35.845
didn't want to learn it again.

00:34:35.845 --> 00:34:37.710
We knew that the
site that we were on

00:34:37.710 --> 00:34:39.540
was basically a backfilled.

00:34:39.540 --> 00:34:42.900
It was a canal, it was a
swamp that was dredged,

00:34:42.900 --> 00:34:45.973
and it was a canal used to bring
the stones to build the Capitol

00:34:45.973 --> 00:34:47.139
and all the other buildings.

00:34:47.139 --> 00:34:52.039
So we knew that we were actually
putting ground on a soggy site.

00:34:52.039 --> 00:34:54.080
And we were developing--
usually as an architect,

00:34:54.080 --> 00:34:56.100
you develop a
foundation of the boat,

00:34:56.100 --> 00:34:57.540
we knew that we were
developing almost a submarine.

00:34:57.540 --> 00:34:59.490
We have to develop and
double-walled system

00:34:59.490 --> 00:34:59.970
to deal with that.

00:34:59.970 --> 00:35:02.178
So we had to kind of bring
in intelligence so that we

00:35:02.178 --> 00:35:03.770
didn't make many mistakes.

00:35:03.770 --> 00:35:05.150
But that's giving you a sense.

00:35:05.150 --> 00:35:07.310
And then with the
content, we were

00:35:07.310 --> 00:35:09.170
the kind of overarching
architects in terms

00:35:09.170 --> 00:35:12.340
of coordinating how the spatial
kind of narrative worked,

00:35:12.340 --> 00:35:14.300
but Applebaum were
the people who

00:35:14.300 --> 00:35:18.140
did the detail of the sonography
of the exhibition design.

00:35:18.140 --> 00:35:20.750
It was their concept and vision.

00:35:20.750 --> 00:35:23.830
So really, what you see
in terms of narrative

00:35:23.830 --> 00:35:26.660
and the specific content is
Ralph Applebaum, who worked

00:35:26.660 --> 00:35:28.350
collaboratively with the team.

00:35:28.350 --> 00:35:31.010
So it's a very
multi-headed system,

00:35:31.010 --> 00:35:32.510
but it's really
exciting because you

00:35:32.510 --> 00:35:35.330
get this incredible intelligence
from different places coming

00:35:35.330 --> 00:35:36.530
together to form this thing.

00:35:39.940 --> 00:35:40.490
Hi Hi.

00:35:40.490 --> 00:35:43.250
A question for you about
construction technology.

00:35:43.250 --> 00:35:46.610
As steel girder construction
and reinforced concrete

00:35:46.610 --> 00:35:49.430
really kind of radically changed
the way architecture worked

00:35:49.430 --> 00:35:53.000
in the last century, what kind
of new upcoming construction

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:54.470
technologies do
you see that will

00:35:54.470 --> 00:35:57.290
make sort of the next
radical shift in what cities

00:35:57.290 --> 00:35:59.040
and buildings look like overall?

00:35:59.040 --> 00:35:59.831
DAVID ADJAYE: Yeah.

00:35:59.831 --> 00:36:02.714
This is the big questions
that are emerging right now.

00:36:02.714 --> 00:36:04.880
I don't think we are 100%
clear about what they are.

00:36:04.880 --> 00:36:10.490
But we know things like if arc
welding and steel and concrete,

00:36:10.490 --> 00:36:14.750
as you said, literally radically
transformed the skyline

00:36:14.750 --> 00:36:16.340
by creating verticality--
essentially,

00:36:16.340 --> 00:36:18.380
it created verticality
and the ability

00:36:18.380 --> 00:36:21.722
to brace and stiffen the
structure as you went up.

00:36:21.722 --> 00:36:23.680
The sort of things that
are happening right now

00:36:23.680 --> 00:36:27.740
is that with elevators,
for instance,

00:36:27.740 --> 00:36:31.610
we're on the precipice for the
first time of elevators that

00:36:31.610 --> 00:36:34.880
no longer just go up and down
but can go sideways, up, down,

00:36:34.880 --> 00:36:35.960
and around things.

00:36:35.960 --> 00:36:38.090
That sounds like nothing,
but that literally

00:36:38.090 --> 00:36:41.270
is a phenomenal
breakthrough which suddenly

00:36:41.270 --> 00:36:44.930
means that we can create
scale and operation in a way

00:36:44.930 --> 00:36:47.390
that actually nobody
could even imagine.

00:36:47.390 --> 00:36:48.290
And those are some of
the things that are

00:36:48.290 --> 00:36:49.539
being thought about right now.

00:36:49.539 --> 00:36:53.364
And these new types of
elevators are being prototyped,

00:36:53.364 --> 00:36:55.280
they're just starting
to come onto the market.

00:36:55.280 --> 00:36:58.490
Mayor Bloomberg has just put a
set in his building in London

00:36:58.490 --> 00:37:00.882
and they're really
extraordinary things.

00:37:00.882 --> 00:37:02.590
Obviously, there's
technology [INAUDIBLE]

00:37:02.590 --> 00:37:06.680
integrated systems make
smart, responsive buildings.

00:37:06.680 --> 00:37:10.280
So the building is not an
inert thing, it's something

00:37:10.280 --> 00:37:13.160
that starts to become, as
it were, it has an ability

00:37:13.160 --> 00:37:15.440
to sense its environment
and respond, both

00:37:15.440 --> 00:37:18.600
to the people in it and
the environment outside.

00:37:18.600 --> 00:37:20.790
So we're able to make
buildings that are,

00:37:20.790 --> 00:37:24.330
I think, much more specific
now and the century

00:37:24.330 --> 00:37:25.635
is going to show more of that.

00:37:25.635 --> 00:37:27.260
And I think with
that, it means that we

00:37:27.260 --> 00:37:30.140
can make buildings that are
much more clearly related

00:37:30.140 --> 00:37:33.170
to their geography, which is
a big problem the 20th century

00:37:33.170 --> 00:37:33.890
couldn't do.

00:37:33.890 --> 00:37:36.230
We were just very much about
creating big clunky things,

00:37:36.230 --> 00:37:39.290
sealing them, pumping air
in them as much as possible,

00:37:39.290 --> 00:37:42.987
and hoping that everybody stayed
in sort of temperature ranges.

00:37:42.987 --> 00:37:45.320
Well, we're now going to be
able to make buildings which

00:37:45.320 --> 00:37:47.390
actually are able to
breathe differently

00:37:47.390 --> 00:37:49.797
in different climates,
different altitudes; be

00:37:49.797 --> 00:37:52.130
able to kind of use the
material science of those places

00:37:52.130 --> 00:37:55.760
to kind of reinforce their
making maybe in terms

00:37:55.760 --> 00:37:58.430
of their fabric, their
wall constituency.

00:37:58.430 --> 00:38:01.110
And we're then going to be able
to make in the 21st century

00:38:01.110 --> 00:38:04.800
geometries that you could only
imagine as drawings in the way

00:38:04.800 --> 00:38:06.800
that maybe the constructivists
imagined drawings

00:38:06.800 --> 00:38:10.130
at the beginning end of the
19th century, early 20th century

00:38:10.130 --> 00:38:13.050
that became buildings at
the end of our 20th century.

00:38:13.050 --> 00:38:15.380
So I'm giving you a
sort of mixed answer

00:38:15.380 --> 00:38:20.212
because I think that the next 25
years is going to reveal a lot,

00:38:20.212 --> 00:38:21.920
but we are at-- the
precipice has already

00:38:21.920 --> 00:38:23.840
seen that it's really
radical going to change.

00:38:23.840 --> 00:38:26.810
We can do density in a way
that people cannot imagine

00:38:26.810 --> 00:38:28.550
and that's already up upon us.

00:38:28.550 --> 00:38:30.950
We're just starting it and
it's going to get more.

