AUDIENCE: My name
is [? Onome ?] and I

00:38:36.103 --> 00:38:38.390
had a question about the
problem-solving process

00:38:38.390 --> 00:38:39.680
for you and your team.

00:38:39.680 --> 00:38:42.080
So one of things you said
that really struck me was you

00:38:42.080 --> 00:38:44.700
focus on solving the
problem for the community

00:38:44.700 --> 00:38:47.160
and then do this
aesthetic around that.

00:38:47.160 --> 00:38:50.570
But from your work,
you're solving problems

00:38:50.570 --> 00:38:52.700
for different kinds of
communities-- for London,

00:38:52.700 --> 00:38:55.190
for New York, Washington
and now you're

00:38:55.190 --> 00:38:57.070
working in Dakar and Accra.

00:38:57.070 --> 00:38:59.840
So how exactly is that
problem-solving and creative

00:38:59.840 --> 00:39:02.240
process when you're
working on solving problems

00:39:02.240 --> 00:39:04.960
for different kinds of people,
different kinds of communities?

00:39:04.960 --> 00:39:05.750
DAVID ADJAYE: Yes.

00:39:05.750 --> 00:39:07.700
It's about being
out in the field.

00:39:07.700 --> 00:39:12.380
One of the things that I
made a very early decision

00:39:12.380 --> 00:39:13.942
was that we're
not a huge company

00:39:13.942 --> 00:39:15.650
and we could just stay
in London and just

00:39:15.650 --> 00:39:16.900
send people out and do things.

00:39:16.900 --> 00:39:19.250
But I decided very
early on that if we

00:39:19.250 --> 00:39:21.560
were going to be in
a continent, then

00:39:21.560 --> 00:39:25.040
we would invest in placing a
team there so that we could

00:39:25.040 --> 00:39:27.740
actually have on the
ground information

00:39:27.740 --> 00:39:30.512
but also develop
relationships on the ground.

00:39:30.512 --> 00:39:31.970
So the reason for
having a New York

00:39:31.970 --> 00:39:35.870
office, the reason for
having an office in Accra

00:39:35.870 --> 00:39:38.180
is because we want to
be much more connected

00:39:38.180 --> 00:39:40.730
and we want to be able to be
responsive in the way in which

00:39:40.730 --> 00:39:43.700
we kind of create the kind of--

00:39:43.700 --> 00:39:46.430
what you need, essentially,
in those collaborations

00:39:46.430 --> 00:39:49.130
is the ability to have
dialogue and to have dialogue

00:39:49.130 --> 00:39:52.831
and response and to
then replay and then

00:39:52.831 --> 00:39:54.080
to have dialogue and response.

00:39:54.080 --> 00:39:55.730
In a way, design is
a kind of process

00:39:55.730 --> 00:39:57.950
of talking it
through and learning

00:39:57.950 --> 00:40:00.870
the lessons, articulating them,
see if it works, and then kind

00:40:00.870 --> 00:40:02.150
of expanding up again.

00:40:02.150 --> 00:40:04.525
So it becomes like a kind of
vortex that's growing bigger

00:40:04.525 --> 00:40:05.860
until you get some solution.

00:40:05.860 --> 00:40:08.730
So that sort of
cyclical kind of journey

00:40:08.730 --> 00:40:10.470
is really important
to have continuity

00:40:10.470 --> 00:40:13.020
and not to have a
sort of disconnect

00:40:13.020 --> 00:40:15.000
that I feel like having
one central office

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:17.490
where you fly in
and out of crates

00:40:17.490 --> 00:40:19.590
you're kind of
still in your world

00:40:19.590 --> 00:40:22.860
and you sort of feel almost
like a space man kind of landing

00:40:22.860 --> 00:40:24.510
somewhere, but you're insulated.

00:40:24.510 --> 00:40:26.190
Whereas I want people
to be almost as it

00:40:26.190 --> 00:40:29.490
we're native, breathing the
air that everybody else is

00:40:29.490 --> 00:40:31.377
breathing and being
in that context.

00:40:31.377 --> 00:40:32.460
It's profoundly important.

00:40:32.460 --> 00:40:35.016
And it seems like nothing,
but actually, it's amazing.

00:40:35.016 --> 00:40:36.390
On the three
continents, the work

00:40:36.390 --> 00:40:38.970
that comes out of the
studio is very different.

00:40:38.970 --> 00:40:40.740
And it's very interesting.

00:40:40.740 --> 00:40:43.860
I'm the kind of main
person, but because it's not

00:40:43.860 --> 00:40:47.400
about an aesthetic kind of
then overwriting and saying,

00:40:47.400 --> 00:40:49.657
this is the look of
Adjaye Associates,

00:40:49.657 --> 00:40:51.240
it's coming from the
solutions that we

00:40:51.240 --> 00:40:53.640
have to make to deal
with the problems

00:40:53.640 --> 00:40:54.660
that we're encountering.

00:40:54.660 --> 00:40:56.100
The work is emerging
differently,

00:40:56.100 --> 00:40:58.410
and for me that
philosophically confirms

00:40:58.410 --> 00:41:01.860
a sort of deeper belief that
architecture of the built

00:41:01.860 --> 00:41:05.640
environment should respond much
more to the geography in terms

00:41:05.640 --> 00:41:08.160
of the kind of terra firma,
but also to the culture that

00:41:08.160 --> 00:41:08.760
is emerging.

00:41:08.760 --> 00:41:11.825
It should find its
aesthetics, find its notion

00:41:11.825 --> 00:41:13.950
through a kind of bigger
sort of thinking about how

00:41:13.950 --> 00:41:16.830
you do things, but it
should find its resolution

00:41:16.830 --> 00:41:19.240
in the way it expresses
itself in different places.

00:41:19.240 --> 00:41:21.300
So for me, I'm in
the experiment also.

00:41:21.300 --> 00:41:23.490
So I'm sort of
half kind of clear,

00:41:23.490 --> 00:41:25.410
but already know
the results that I

00:41:25.410 --> 00:41:28.770
have make me believe that
it's really the right way.

